**Version Used**: 
VS 17.4.3
**Steps to Reproduce**:

Start with this code:
```csharp
    public class Foo1 : IDate {
        public DateTimeOffset? Date { get; set; }
    }

    public class Foo2 : IDate {
        public DateTimeOffset? Date { get; set; }
    }

    public interface IDate { 
        public DateTimeOffset? Date { get; set; }
    }
```

and rename ```Foo1.Date``` to ```Start_Date```

**Expected Behavior**:
My entire source code should now look like this
```csharp
    public class Foo1 : IDate {
        public DateTimeOffset? Start_Date { get; set; } // <- Changed
        DateTimeOffset? IDate.Date { get => Start_Date; set => Start_Date = value; } // <- Added
    }

    public class Foo2 : IDate {
        public DateTimeOffset? Date { get; set; }
    }

    public interface IDate { 
        public DateTimeOffset? Date { get; set; }
    }
```
**Actual Behavior**:

My entire codebase now looks like this:

```csharp
    public class Foo1 : IDate {
        public DateTimeOffset? Start_Date { get; set; } // <- Changed
    }

    public class Foo2 : IDate {
        public DateTimeOffset? Start_Date { get; set; } // <- Changed
    }

    public interface IDate { 
        public DateTimeOffset? Start_Date { get; set; } // <- Changed
    }
```

This is super dangerous because it not only refactors the current class, it also refactors the interface and all implementor of the interface.

