In a non-generic scenario, when receiver is a nullable value type, it is unwrapped and the access is performed on a copy of the underlying non-null value. Therefore, the side effects are never preserved in the original nullable instance. I think Test2 is supposed to make a copy of the receiver when it is a nullable value type at runtime, but, unlike Test1, it doesn't do that.

